1. The Core Principle (applies everywhere)

LLMs do not persist invariants unless they are:

explicitly stated,

repeatedly reinforced,

and checked against outputs.

So protocol usage always has three layers:

Anchor â€“ establish rules of engagement

Operate â€“ do the actual work

Verify / Reassert â€“ correct drift when it appears

Different systems just change how often you need to do step 3.

2. Usage by System Type
A. ChatGPT / Claude / Gemini (Standard Chat UI)

Characteristics

Large but lossy context window

Soft safety redirection possible

Invariants decay over long threads

Best Strategy

Front-load a compact protocol anchor

Reassert lightly when drift appears

Use behavioral checks, not meta-arguments

Recommended Pattern

One system-style anchor prompt

One operational reminder phrase

One drift correction phrase

B. API / Local LLMs (Ollama, LM Studio, vLLM)

Characteristics

Deterministic across runs

Full control over system prompt

No hidden â€œtone repairâ€ layers

Best Strategy

